{"source_key":"sha256-ea08d35f42d5530fbe92c80d4f5b27e9","record_index":168,"record_hash":"sha256:6ea6f02f9e0fbf4555b55c9d25a1b424abcc90bcf8e256951f62f83217311543","timestamp":"2026-05-24T15:31:07.035Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Update File: agent-trail.md\n@@\n ## MVP Contract\n \n Input:\n \n ```text\n@@\n - pass PR facts to `but-agentlog` so it can construct review-target candidates,\n   then query those candidates plus the PR head branch\n - rank review-target matches above branch-only matches\n - render a generated snapshot page with overview plus session/turn drill-down\n - serve the stable PR route as the user-facing route; keep immutable snapshot\n   ids internal for v1\n+\n+Repository reality for Forge:\n+\n+- Forge is a Next.js 15 App Router application with Node route handlers and a\n+  small Rust CLI workspace. It is not currently a Rust web server and it has no\n+  NAPI/native-module packaging path.\n+- The v1 backend should be a compartmentalized Agent Trail vertical:\n+  `lib/agent-trail/*`, `app/api/agent-trail/*`, and a future\n+  `app/[owner]/[repo]/pull/[number]` page. Do not blend this into the existing\n+  Cloud sync/auth/workspace flows.\n+- The existing code.storage Cloud sync path is private per-user sync. It is not\n+  the public GitHub metadata source for Agent Trail. Public Agent Trail should\n+  fetch the public GitHub repository's `refs/meta/main` directly.\n+- For the first build, prefer a purpose-built Rust JSON helper binary over\n+  NAPI. Node should orchestrate HTTP, GitHub lookup, route handling, caching,\n+  and UI; Rust should own `but-agentlog` interpretation and return an\n+  allowlisted projection. NAPI can wait until there is a measured need for an\n+  in-process native module.\n \n Snapshot identity should be stable and derived from repository identity, pull\n request identity/version, metadata state, projection version, and selected\n evidence. A plausible initial tuple is:\n@@\n For GitHub PRs, Forge should pass PR facts to `but-agentlog`: forge host,\n repository identity, PR number, base branch, head branch, and head SHA.\n `but-agentlog` should construct the stored review-target candidates.\n \n-For example, PR `13936` may correspond to a review key like:\n+Do not assume that a GitHub PR number is itself a GitButler review id. In the\n+current `but-agentlog` implementation, known target shapes include:\n \n ```text\n-gitbutler-review:13936\n+ref:refs/heads/<pr-head-branch>\n+pull-request:ref:refs/heads/<pr-head-branch>#<number>\n+gitbutler-review:<review-id>\n ```\n \n-or to other stored review-target shapes supported by captured GitButler\n-metadata. These string forms are explanatory, not a Forge-owned storage\n-contract. Forge should use `but-agentlog` target constructors or query APIs once\n-those exist, not hand-roll GitButler agentlog key normalization.\n+`gitbutler-review:<review-id>` is only directly constructible when Forge knows\n+the GitButler review id. A GitHub PR URL usually gives Forge the PR number and\n+head branch, so the buildable v1 review candidate is the `pull-request:...#N`\n+shape plus the branch target. These string forms are explanatory, not a\n+Forge-owned storage contract. Forge should use `but-agentlog` target\n+constructors or query APIs once those exist, not hand-roll GitButler agentlog\n+key normalization.\n \n This review target is optional because captured metadata may not always include\n review information. When it is present, it is the strongest first lookup for a\n PR-scoped Agent Trail.\n@@\n The server should fetch public PR metadata from GitHub, resolve the PR head\n branch, and search both useful MVP targets in one pass:\n \n ```text\n-review target: gitbutler-review:13936\n+review target: pull-request:ref:refs/heads/<pr-head-branch>#13936\n branch target: ref:refs/heads/<pr-head-branch>\n ```\n \n V1 should search both when PR metadata is available, then rank review-target\n hits above branch-only hits. If GitHub PR lookup fails, v1 should fail closed\n@@\n The server side of the Agent Trail application is expected to use the\n `but-agentlog` crate to interact with captured data. It should call\n `but-agentlog` read/query/projection primitives rather than reimplementing\n GitMeta key parsing, transcript normalization, target verification, or bounded\n record hydration.\n \n-Today `but-agentlog` is mostly CLI-shaped. The Agent Trail MVP needs a small\n-public library API for server use. Add that API before Forge renders public\n-Agent Trail pages. Do not shell out to `but agentlog` from Forge.\n+Today `but-agentlog` is mostly CLI-shaped: the crate publicly exports\n+`Command`, `RelatedSessionTarget`, and `run_from_dir`, while the useful\n+timeline, records, target, and related-session types are mostly `pub(crate)`.\n+The CLI path also resolves a worktree and defaults targets through local\n+GitButler status, which is the wrong boundary for a hosted PR page.\n+\n+The Agent Trail MVP needs a small public library API for server use. Add that\n+API before Forge renders public Agent Trail pages. Do not shell out to\n+`but agentlog` from Forge. Shelling out to a purpose-built Forge-owned Rust\n+helper binary is acceptable for v1 if that binary calls the new library API and\n+returns the public projection JSON.\n \n The likely API surface is:\n \n - accept PR facts and construct stored review and branch query targets\n-- find related sessions for multiple targets\n+- construct both `pull-request:ref:refs/heads/<head>#<number>` and\n+  `ref:refs/heads/<head>` targets without exposing those strings as Forge\n+  contract\n+- optionally accept a known GitButler review id later and add\n+  `gitbutler-review:<review-id>` to the candidate set\n+- find related sessions for multiple targets in one call\n - return match reasons per session and turn\n - return compact public/read projections for sessions and turns\n - provide bounded exact record drill-down from stable handles\n-- support server-prepared GitMeta sources without requiring a worktree or CLI\n-  default-branch discovery\n+- support server-prepared GitMeta sources without requiring a checked-out\n+  worktree or CLI default-branch discovery\n+\n+`but-agentlog` should also change capture/query behavior so a branch with both\n+`review_id` and `pull_request` indexes both useful review targets. The current\n+environment capture shape effectively picks the review id when present, which\n+means a PR-number lookup can miss the strongest evidence unless Forge falls\n+back through the branch target.\n \n Ranking policy belongs to Agent Trail. `but-agentlog` should provide verified\n matches and match reasons; Forge should rank review-target matches above\n branch-only matches for the page.\n@@\n Possible linkage paths:\n \n-- short term: depend on the GitButler repository as a pinned Cargo git\n-  dependency and import the `but-agentlog` package\n - local development: use a path dependency from Forge to a local GitButler\n   checkout\n+- short term production: depend on the GitButler repository as a pinned Cargo\n+  git dependency and import the `but-agentlog` package\n - if the full GitButler workspace dependency graph is too heavy, split a smaller\n   `but-agentlog-read` or `but-agenttrail-core` crate that owns target\n   construction, verified lookup, match reasons, and public projections\n \n@@\n The important rule is no copied reader logic. Forge may own Agent Trail\n snapshot, visibility, and UI policy, but the canonical storage interpretation\n should stay in `but-agentlog`.\n+\n+The clean Forge-side Rust boundary is:\n+\n+```text\n+Next route/API -> TypeScript AgentTrail service -> Rust projection helper JSON\n+```\n+\n+The helper should accept a JSON request containing the prepared repo path or\n+GitMeta source, resolved metadata OID, PR facts, limits, and projection version.\n+It should return only the public Agent Trail projection. It should not perform\n+GitHub HTTP, own snapshot retention, render UI, or know about Forge sessions.\n \n Build may start for public repos and publicly fetchable metadata. Private repo,\n team, explicit-share, and richer publication flows are later work.\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T15:31:07.035Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"apply_patch"}}}